<seg id="1">CASA suggests seats for kids on aircraft</seg>
<seg id="2">AUSTRALIA'S aviation safety watchdog is considering whether young children should use car-like seat capsules when travelling on aircraft.</seg>
<seg id="3">The Civil Aviation Safety Authority (CASA) has released for public comment a draft document suggesting parents do more than carry infants on their laps using a supplementary seatbelt.</seg>
<seg id="4">"A child up to age four would be more effectively protected if seated in a child restraint system," the draft, released on Friday, says.</seg>
<seg id="5">An adult and child using the common supplementary seatbelt method face increased risk of injury during an aircraft accident, CASA found.</seg>
<seg id="6">"The supplemental loop belt is even less effective for the infant as their skeletal structure is unable to cope with any significant load ... and the crushing forces applied by the adult torso," it said.</seg>
<seg id="7">While the seatbelt method was found to provide "adequate restraint" for an infant during turbulence or a minor incident, an individual restraint in a separate passenger seat offered more protection.</seg>
<seg id="8">CASA said both forward and rear-facing child seats, along with booster seats commonly used in vehicles, could be suitable for use in aircraft.</seg>
<seg id="9">The draft document also found infants were safer if they didn't travel in aisle seats.</seg>
<seg id="10">"They could easily be injured by a passing person or galley cart," the draft document said.</seg>
<seg id="11">A standard seat is recommended for a child once they reach age four, 18kgs and 100cm.</seg>
<seg id="12">The draft document can be found at www.casa.gov.au and submissions close on November 11.</seg>
</doc>
