<seg id="1">MP Palmer to lay his interests bare</seg>
<seg id="2">Political News</seg>
<seg id="3">Wealthy businessman Clive Palmer will be forced to disclose a minefield of potential conflicts of interests in his role as a federal MP, with directorships of no fewer than 74 private companies involved in aviation, sport, mining, shipping, real estate and tourism.</seg>
<seg id="4">Concerns about the influence of Mr Palmer's interests on his political decisions were raised on Friday by Liberal National MP Wyatt Roy.</seg>
<seg id="5">Clive is an individual who is clearly pretty self-interested.</seg>
<seg id="6">I think there are pretty serious questions about that," Mr Roy said.</seg>
<seg id="7">A Fairfax Media investigation of Mr Palmer's wealth found his investments stretch from cane farms on the Sunshine Coast to coalfields in central Queensland, a Tahitian resort, prospecting operations in offshore gasfields, Chinese ship builders and Zeppelin airships.</seg>
<seg id="8">In the past, the self-proclaimed billionaire has been circumspect about the source and nature of his wealth.</seg>
<seg id="9">But he will be required to submit a detailed list of his assets within 28 days of being asked to swear an oath of affirmation as a federal MP.</seg>
<seg id="10">Using company and property searches and statements from Mr Palmer and his companies, Fairfax has come up with a snapshot of a Palmer register.</seg>
<seg id="11">The assets will include substantial interests in mining and metal refining, which will bring into sharp focus his personal and party positions on the carbon and mining taxes.</seg>
<seg id="12">Mr Roy, 23, said Mr Palmer should stop thinking of himself as a "novelty" act and model his parliamentary behaviour on that of former Australian Democrats leader Don Chipp.</seg>
<seg id="13">"His term in Parliament should be about the results he can deliver for his electorate," Mr Roy said.</seg>
<seg id="14">Mr Palmer responded: "Well poor old Wyatt's ... only a young boy that's never had a job."</seg>
</doc>
