<doc docid="4d1825860d72694a4dc1e27997888f99" genre="news" origlang="xx">
<seg id="1">Bank stocks" stellar run hits the buffers</seg>
<seg id="2">Investigations, litigation, fines: past misdemeanours and a wave of regulatory action have buffeted banks" share prices this week.</seg>
<seg id="3">The stellar run enjoyed by European bank stocks, in particular, may finally have run out of road.</seg>
<seg id="4">Barclays, Lloyds, Royal Bank of Scotland, Deutsche Bank, UBS and Credit Suisse are among the biggest names in the industry whose shares have suffered over the past week, amid disappointing results and an escalating probe into alleged rigging of the foreign exchange market.</seg>
<seg id="5">IN European Equities</seg>
<seg id="6">The septimana horribilis caps a heady year for Europe's financial sector.</seg>
<seg id="7">Investor confidence in the eurozone has recovered following a promise by Mario Draghi, European Central Bank president, to do "whatever it takes" to save the euro.</seg>
<seg id="8">Indeed, the biggest European banks - as measured by the Eurofirst 300 banks index - have outperformed the wider European stock market by over two percentage points for the year to date.</seg>
<seg id="9">But, over the past three months, that outperformance has slipped to just a fraction of a percentage point, eroded by a slowdown in fixed income trading, the fall-out from the Libor rate fixing scandal and fears over further capital demands from regulators.</seg>
<seg id="10">"Relative to US banks, European valuations are looking punchy," says Ronit Ghose, banks analyst at Citi, "That doesn't mean banks are "sells" but to justify continuing outperformance we need to see earnings upgrades and third-quarter results have been a messy set of numbers."</seg>
<seg id="11">Top of the worry list are lawsuits.</seg>
<seg id="12">Following JP Morgan's $13bn settlement with US authorities, investors are concerned that a volley of litigation by national regulators in Europe could signal the opening salvo of a wider barrage.</seg>
<seg id="13">"We have just stepped on a litigation landmine [although] it's taken a little time to dawn on the market," says a senior European banking analyst.</seg>
<seg id="14">This is something that banks have to set aside significant earnings for and the question is whether or not they can afford it at the same time when they're building [capital] reserves for other things.</seg>
<seg id="15">Swiss banks have been among the worst fallers.</seg>
<seg id="16">UBS and Credit Suisse tumbled nearly 10 per cent and 4 per cent, respectively, this week in dollar terms.</seg>
<seg id="17">Deutsche Bank, whose share price fell by 3.6 per cent over the same period, has set aside €500m towards possible penalties in relation to global regulators" investigations into the Libor scandal that has seen Barclays, UBS and Royal Bank of Scotland pay hundreds of millions in fines.</seg>
<seg id="18">Now there is the deepening probe into foreign exchange trading.</seg>
<seg id="19">Friday's disclosure that six Barclays traders have been suspended has added to a sense among bankers and investors that an industry-wide investigation is rapidly spiralling into a scandal that might match the scale of the Libor saga.</seg>
<seg id="20">Barclays, UBS and Deutsche have said they are involved in the forex probe, with US banks Citi and JP Morgan confirming on Friday that they, too, were working with regulators.</seg>
<seg id="21">Regulators in the UK, US, Switzerland and Hong Kong are involved in the investigation.</seg>
<seg id="22">Alberto Gallo, head of European macro credit research at Royal Bank of Scotland., says the unpredictable nature of the probes makes assessing banks" provisions uncertain.</seg>
<seg id="23">"Unlike bad loan charges, it's hard to estimate whether provisions for litigation are accurate or not, given their idiosyncratic nature," he says.</seg>
<seg id="24">In addition to the legal worries declines in fixed income trading have hit profits at BNP Paribas, Credit Suisse, JPMorgan, Citigroup and Deutsche Bank.</seg>
<seg id="25">This, combined with subdued markets and a move towards central clearing, has prompted many banks to rethink how they run their debt trading.</seg>
<seg id="26">UBS exitd large parts of its fixed-income business last year.</seg>
<seg id="27">Credit Suisse this month unveiled an overhaul of its own, focused on a restructuring of its rates business, which is the lowest-returning part of its investment bank.</seg>
<seg id="28">Lying in the background is European regulators" upcoming review of banks" balance sheets and stress tests.</seg>
<seg id="29">The tests, due to begin next year, are expected to lead to further capital raising.</seg>
<seg id="30">"Institutions which have large balance sheets but low risk-weighted assets like Barclays or Deutsche Bank will be penalised and pushed to delever or raise more capital," says Mr Gallo.</seg>
<seg id="31">Stricter regulation and higher risk weights will also impact the revenue mix of banks, and institutions which generate most of their revenues from investment banking and trading will have to diversify.</seg>
<seg id="32">Supporters maintain the regulatory review is a good thing in the longer term.</seg>
<seg id="33">It will, they argue, bolster transparency and harmonise national rules on risk weighting assets, capital buffers and the "bail-in" of creditors when a bank defaults.</seg>
<seg id="34">Huw van Steenis, an analyst at Morgan Stanley, says that banks" stalling share prices constitute a bump on the road to recovery, rather than a pothole: "Uncertainty always causes a discount [in share prices]."</seg>
<seg id="35">I think there's a lot of tactical selling by investors but the overall strategy is still long European financials.</seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="4d49320981b7e7d145d578eee8085f70" genre="news" origlang="xx">
