<seg id="1">CFTC hit by budget constraints</seg>
<seg id="2">The Commodity Futures Trading Commission may have to forgo or delay certain investigations because of budget constraints as the agency works on setting priorities for the new fiscal year, agency officials said.</seg>
<seg id="3">The pressure is affecting morale and the CFTC's ability to retain and attract talent, they added.</seg>
<seg id="4">Employee sentiment was already down since the CFTC was the only regulatory agency that was essentially closed during the US government shutdown earlier this month.</seg>
<seg id="5">IN Markets Regulation</seg>
<seg id="6">"One of the greatest threats to well-functioning, open, and competitive swaps and futures markets is that the agency tasked with overseeing them is not sized to the task at hand," said CFTC Chairman Gary Gensler in a speech Thursday, who added the agency has had to shrink 5 per cent because of budget issues.</seg>
<seg id="7">The agency is going through a strategic planning process, which is usually a routine practice.</seg>
<seg id="8">But this year, the agency is being forced to make tough choices because it does not have the money to fund all of its duties, especially because it now has added responsibilities under the Dodd-Frank legislation, said CFTC Commissioner Bart Chilton.</seg>
<seg id="9">That may mean the CFTC will have to farm out certain issues to others, like the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, or rely on the National Futures Association to take on more self-regulatory functions because the CFTC cannot perform those duties, according to Mr Chilton.</seg>
<seg id="10">We will not be able to do everything Congress instructed us to do.</seg>
<seg id="11">"Everything is going to be slowed down," Mr Chilton said.</seg>
<seg id="12">There is going to be a lot more trial by fire rather than good, thoughtful governance because we just don't have the people.</seg>
<seg id="13">Another agency official said there would be "significant delays" in cases the CFTC investigates and in less egregious allegations, the agency may have to forgo enforcement efforts all together.</seg>
<seg id="14">The CFTC has stepped up enforcement cases in recent years and recently handed over $1bn in settlement money to the US Treasury.</seg>
<seg id="15">That includes hundreds of millions of dollars in fines related to the manipulation of Libor rates.</seg>
<seg id="16">In the meantime, several companies seeking clarifications from the CFTC on recently issued rules regarding swaps dealer registration and other matters have been waiting more than six months for an answer, people familiar with the matter said.</seg>
<seg id="17">"It's hard to make plans and figure out what is going on when all we get is silence," said one energy firm that is trying to find out if it needs to register as a swaps dealer.</seg>
<seg id="18">The CFTC is concentrating its resources on finishing rulemaking requirements from the Dodd-Frank bill, and therefore, does not have the staff to answer questions in a timely manner.</seg>
<seg id="19">Mr Gensler has also complained that the CFTC does not have the money to visit swaps dealers to ensure compliance.</seg>
<seg id="20">The agency, which has about 700 employees, relies on Congress for its budget appropriations.</seg>
<seg id="21">Earlier this year, the Republican-dominated House of Representatives approved maintaining the current CFTC funding level of $195m, which is less than the Obama administration's 2014 fiscal year budget request of $315m.</seg>
<seg id="22">As a result, CFTC employees may be furloughed for as many as 14 days in this fiscal year, which began on October 1.</seg>
<seg id="23">Because Republican lawmakers have complained about CFTC over-reach, it is unlikely that they will get the full budget requested by the government.</seg>
</doc>
