<seg id="1">"Allegory and Illusion," at the Rubin Museum</seg>
<seg id="2">Alkazi Collection of Photography</seg>
<seg id="3">Allegory and Illusion, at the Rubin Museum, focuses on 19th- and early-20th-century photography in South Asia, like these paint-enriched portraits of Dev Shamshere Rana and his wife Krishna Kumari of Nepal.</seg>
<seg id="4">A new show of portrait photography at the Rubin Museum of Art, "Allegory and Illusion" is a fascinating little piece of a very complicated puzzle.</seg>
<seg id="5">Ostensibly a focused, regional exhibition, it has much to say about the larger relationship between photography and colonialism (a subject big enough to fill several museums).</seg>
<seg id="6">Featuring material from India, Burma (now Myanmar), Ceylon (now Sri Lanka), and Nepal, the show, whose subtitle is "Early Portrait Photography From South Asia," tracks the spread of photography from the mid-19th to early-20th centuries through areas that were then under British rule or influence.</seg>
<seg id="7">It includes many different forms of early photography, representing an array of markets and social classes: There are grand portraits of Nepalese royals, and palm-size cartes de visite for the masses; ethnographic albums by British photographers; and hand-painted photographs from Indian portrait studios.</seg>
<seg id="8">Some of those objects fit the standard narrative of early photography, the one we know from countless exhibitions on America and Western Europe.</seg>
<seg id="9">The cartes de visite craze, for instance, parallels the one that swept America around the time of the Civil War.</seg>
<seg id="10">And a portrait of an Afghan tribesman by the British photographer Randolph Bezzant Holmes demonstrates fidelity to the pictorial aesthetic of Victorian photographers like Julia Margaret Cameron (who was, it's worth noting, the daughter of an East India Company official).</seg>
<seg id="11">Other items on display make photography out to be a tool of colonialist suppression; the 1868 ethnographic album "People of India," with its summary treatment of some 480 different castes, races and tribes, or the portrait of a snake charmer that treats photography as an extension of the "Company School" tradition of picturesque paintings made for East India Company officials.</seg>
<seg id="12">But still others show South Asians adapting photography to their own art traditions.</seg>
<seg id="13">This is particularly true of the portraits from India, which are often painted over in vivid colors and sometimes even embellished (as in a portrait of a Gujarati nobleman whose costume and sword have been adorned with velvet, sequins and gold-colored wire.)</seg>
<seg id="14">As the curators note, some of these works might be mistaken for miniature paintings.</seg>
<seg id="15">The photography scholar Christopher Pinney, writing in the catalog, goes so far as to refer to photography in colonial India as "a form of late painting."</seg>
<seg id="16">In a court portrait of Maharajah Venkat Raman Singh, the ruler of the princely state of Rewa, the figure is isolated against a flat, color-blocked background, and the underlying gelatin silver print is barely visible beneath the layers of oil paint.</seg>
<seg id="17">India, not surprisingly, is the source of roughly half the works in the show (which was organized by Beth Citron, an assistant curator at the Rubin, and Rahaab Allana, curator of the Alkazi Foundation for the Arts in New Delhi.)</seg>
<seg id="18">Most of the photographs from India, Burma and Nepal are studio portraits.</seg>
<seg id="19">But the images from Ceylon, most of them taken by British photography studios like Skeen and Scowen, place figures in the landscape - the better to portray this small island colony, a center of coffee and tea production, as a land of plenty.</seg>
<seg id="20">One picture shows a group of aboriginal Vedda hunters posed outdoors with their bows and arrows.</seg>
<seg id="21">Another, less typical, depicts a boy from the "untouchable" Rodiya caste; a close-up, three-quarters view of his face, it seems more intimate and humane than the other ethnographic photos on view.</seg>
<seg id="22">The photographs from Nepal, in contrast, offer a glimpse of the royal life (and particularly the lives of princesses and maharanis, who were cloistered according to the custom of purdah).</seg>
<seg id="23">Nearly all of the images are formal court portraits, in which unsmiling faces peer out from the voluminous embroidered robes and heavy tiaras.</seg>
<seg id="24">What little we see of early photography in Burma comes mostly from the Italian-born British war photographer Felice Beato, who traveled throughout Asia (documenting the Crimean War right after Roger Fenton) and eventually set up shop in Burma.</seg>
<seg id="25">Most of the anonymous young women in his studio photographs wear traditional sarongs and clutch cheroots, or long Burmese cigars; their outfits may be a form of "passive resistance," as the curators suggest, but titles like "The Belle of Mandalay" imply a foreigner's exoticizing gaze.</seg>
<seg id="26">"Allegory and Illusion" presents us with many such conundrums: images that make it hard to tell whether photography was an accessory or a deterrent to colonial rule.</seg>
<seg id="27">This might be true even of the many images in the show that are, to us, overtly ethnographic; Mr. Pinney points out, in his essay, that India did not have much of a portrait culture before colonialism, and that its more "anonymized" tradition of figurative art may lend itself to less dehumanizing interpretations of these photographs.</seg>
<seg id="28">And the show, drawn entirely from the Alkazi's photography collection, has some notable gaps.</seg>
<seg id="29">What kind of portraiture, for instance, was happening outside the palaces in Nepal?</seg>
<seg id="30">At times, you wish the curators had just focused on India rather than offering a fragmentary picture of photography in some of the other British colonies.</seg>
<seg id="31">But, in the end, that's all right, because this is a teaser of a show: a call for further study of early photography, in South Asia and elsewhere in the colonial world.</seg>
<seg id="32">With time, you hope, the other pieces will fall into place.</seg>
<seg id="33">"Allegory and Illusion: Early Portrait Photography from South Asia" runs through Feb.</seg>
<seg id="34">10 at the Rubin Museum of Art, 150 West 17th Street, Chelsea; 212-620-5000, rmanyc.org.</seg>
</doc>
