<seg id="1">Tablets on a Plane - NYTimes.com</seg>
<seg id="2">It took a while, but common sense has finally prevailed when it comes to the rules governing travelers" use of electronic devices on planes.</seg>
<seg id="3">The Federal Aviation Administration announced on Thursday that passengers could soon be allowed to use tablet computers, e-books, music players and other devices in planes at almost all times as long as their wireless functions are disabled by putting the device in "airplane mode."</seg>
<seg id="4">The editorial board backed changing F.A.A."s policies earlier this month.</seg>
<seg id="5">The F.A.A. has long resisted allowing passengers to use electronic devices once plane doors are closed and before aircraft reach 10,000 feet even when the gadgets were not transmitting data.</seg>
<seg id="6">To many passengers the restriction seemed illogical and it was widely flouted.</seg>
<seg id="7">Under the new F.A.A. guidelines, airlines can start allowing the use of electronic devices once they have proved to the agency that the gadgets will not interfere with navigation systems, avionics and other equipment.</seg>
<seg id="8">The agency expects that will happen by the end of the year in the case of many airlines.</seg>
<seg id="9">Passengers will still be forbidden from making cellphone calls on planes at all times under Federal Communications Commission rules.</seg>
<seg id="10">But they can connect their phones and other devices to the wireless Internet services provided (for a fee) by many airlines once planes have reached 10,000 feet.</seg>
<seg id="11">The new guidelines sensibly allow airline crews to require passengers to shut down devices in special circumstances like during periods of low-visibility, when some landing systems may not be able to tolerate electronic interference.</seg>
<seg id="12">At least some of the credit for the F.A.A."s change of heart belongs to my colleague Nick Bilton who questioned the agency's policies on electronic devices as far back as 2011.</seg>
<seg id="13">He wrote:</seg>
<seg id="14">New technologies are often greeted with fear and that is certainly true of a disruptive technology like cellphones.</seg>
<seg id="15">Yet rules that are decades old persist without evidence to support the idea that someone reading an e-book or playing a video game during takeoff or landing is jeopardizing safety.</seg>
</doc>
