<seg id="1">Canceled U.S. health plans are disruptive part of reform -Cigna CEO</seg>
<seg id="2">Thu Oct 31, 2013 2:25pm EDT</seg>
<seg id="3">(Reuters) - The hundreds of thousands of Americans whose individual insurance policies will be canceled as Obamacare takes full effect next year are experiencing a disruptive element of healthcare reform, the head of health insurer Cigna said on Thursday.</seg>
<seg id="4">In the past week, reports of pending plan cancellations have become a political problem for President Barack Obama, who promised years ago as he was pushing to pass the healthcare law that Americans who liked their health plans could keep them.</seg>
<seg id="5">While that remains true for most people with insurance, a small percentage of the 17 million Americans with individual policies are now getting notice that they will terminate next year because they do not comply with new benefits required by Obamacare.</seg>
<seg id="6">Many insurers are offering new, compliant policies to replace those that are expiring, but they may be significantly more expensive.</seg>
<seg id="7">Nearly half of U.S. consumers with individual health plans are also expected to qualify for tax credits to buy insurance on new state exchanges under Obamacare.</seg>
<seg id="8">"When you are that individual who has a benefit plan and it's working for you and your family at your current life stage and you are told that you no longer have that choice, that's disruptive and that's the environment that as a country we are going through right now," Cigna Chief Executive David Cordani said in an interview.</seg>
<seg id="9">Cigna had about 232,000 people in individual policies at the end of September, according to company filings.</seg>
<seg id="10">Competitor WellPoint Inc, which operates 14 Blue Cross Blue Shield licenses including the Anthem and Empire brands, has about 1.8 million people in individual plans.</seg>
<seg id="11">Aetna Inc, which bought smaller insurer Coventry earlier this year, has 650,000 members in these plans and will drop about 50,000 members when it exits the California market at the end of this year.</seg>
<seg id="12">In defending the healthcare law on Wednesday, Obama said it was not to blame for the plan cancellations, and that the real fault lies with "bad apple" insurers who were allowed to sell cut-rate policies that offered minimal coverage for people when they needed them the most.</seg>
<seg id="13">Cordani declined to comment on Obama's remarks, but noted that individual plans have been subjected to numerous new requirements under the law.</seg>
<seg id="14">States determine the minimum eligible benefits and there are federal requirements, so in some states elements such as the size of the deductible could disqualify an individual plan for 2014.</seg>
<seg id="15">"It's as simple as that," he said.</seg>
<seg id="16">WellPoint and Aetna declined to comment on specifics about policy cancellations or about the president's comments.</seg>
<seg id="17">Cordani said that Cigna has a small individual insurance business and is not significantly impacted by needing to cancel these plans.</seg>
<seg id="18">In addition, it has about 125,000 employer-sponsored plans that will end on January 1, 2014 because they do not comply with the law.</seg>
<seg id="19">These plans typically targeted seasonal or hourly workers, he said, and it was clear from when the health reform law was passed in 2010 that they were going away.</seg>
<seg id="20">Reporting by Caroline Humer; Editing by Michele Gershberg and Cynthia Osterman</seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="898c99964d92ae5c64ba71fd76d11876" genre="news" origlang="xx">
<seg id="1">Brett Morris steps up bid to lure brother Josh back to St George Illawarra</seg>
<seg id="2">Centre stage: Josh Morris (right) will play his first Test in two years, against Fiji this weekend, while his twin Brett will be rested.</seg>
<seg id="3">Manchester: If Josh Morris does end up switching back to St George Illawarra when his contract at Canterbury expires next year, his twin brother Brett should ask the Dragons hierarchy for a bonus, with Josh declaring a "desire" to once again play alongside Brett.</seg>
<seg id="4">Brett is using the time spent in camp with the Australian team in the UK to persuade his brother to again link with him in the Red V. It's been five years since Josh last played for St George Illawarra, and the Canterbury outside back said he was enticed by the thought of playing alongise his brother again.</seg>
<seg id="5">"There is always pressure from him," Josh said.</seg>
<seg id="6">I probably put just as much as he puts on.</seg>
<seg id="7">It's all in good fun.</seg>
<seg id="8">Brett is pretty up to date with all [the rumours].</seg>
<seg id="9">I don't have Twitter and he gets on and retweets - I think that's what it's called - and he likes to start rumours and spread fires.</seg>
<seg id="10">It's all harmless fun.</seg>
<seg id="11">He would really like me to go back there and I'm off-contract next year.</seg>
<seg id="12">I will just concentrate on footy while I'm over here and then having a good year at the Bulldogs.</seg>
<seg id="13">There is always going to be a desire to play in the same side together.</seg>
<seg id="14">Two Test matches and a handful of Origin appearances alongside each other is enough to whet their appetite for now.</seg>
<seg id="15">Playing apart has helped their careers progress, according to Josh.</seg>
<seg id="16">"It works better at the moment with us at different clubs because it gives us a goal to strive for to play rep footy with one another," Josh said.</seg>
<seg id="17">We want to be named in these sides and in the Origin sides.</seg>
<seg id="18">We are individuals more in different teams and judged on that rather than being a package deal for one club.</seg>
<seg id="19">While they don't have to wear coloured wrist bands to help identify them like did when their first burst into first grade at St George Illawarra, their identity still remains a source of confusion for some teammates, particularly Canberra rookie Josh Papalii.</seg>
<seg id="20">The twins are roommates for the first time since their teens.</seg>
<seg id="21">"We shared rooms until we were about 14 or 15 and a couple of wrestles here and there meant a couple of holes in the wall," Josh said.</seg>
<seg id="22">He got kicked out because I was cleaner so I get the big room.</seg>
<seg id="23">I was pretty happy with that.</seg>
<seg id="24">He is messier than me but he has gotten a lot better since he moved out of home and had a little kid and got engaged.</seg>
<seg id="25">He has changed a fair bit.</seg>
<seg id="26">One position they won't be fighting over is playing fullback at their respective clubs.</seg>
<seg id="27">Injuries have meant the brothers have dabbled in the No.1 jersey at times.</seg>
<seg id="28">Josh played a handful of games at the back for Canterbury this year but doesn't want to be a permanent replacement following Ben Barba's defection to Canterbury.</seg>
<seg id="29">"Long-term I don't see myself as a fullback," Morris said.</seg>
<seg id="30">I played a bit a fair bit at the end of the year filling in when Benny was injured.</seg>
<seg id="31">I did enjoy it but it's not a position I see myself playing in a regular basis.</seg>
<seg id="32">I think Des knows that and I'm sure he has his eyes on someone.</seg>
<seg id="33">Having watched Australia's opening pool game from the sidelines, Josh will make his Test return against Fiji on Saturday night (Sunday, 7am AEDT).</seg>
<seg id="34">Brett has been rested.</seg>
<seg id="35">Poll: Will Australia win the Rugby League World Cup in 2013?</seg>
<seg id="36">Total votes: 18.</seg>
<seg id="37">Vote now: Rugby League World Cup 2013</seg>
</doc>
