<seg id="1">Derby winner must beat pain barrier</seg>
<seg id="2">Tough test: Fiveandahalfstar wins the 2012 Victoria Derby.</seg>
<seg id="3">The Victoria Derby is a true classic race and a genuine test of the young thoroughbred.</seg>
<seg id="4">The race, run over 2500 metres, is testing because, to be competitive, the horse needs to have a blend of sprinting and staying abilities, skeletal maturity, a relaxed racing attitude, and the ability to cope with pain and perform, which is not always a characteristic of young horses.</seg>
<seg id="5">A three-year-old racehorse is still a juvenile and relatively immature.</seg>
<seg id="6">The average horse's life span is somewhere between 25-30 years and throughout that life span there are many developmental changes as the horse grows and matures.</seg>
<seg id="7">A simple analogy would be to say a three-year-old racehorse has the skeletal maturity of a 10-year-old child.</seg>
<seg id="8">Bone is a very dynamic tissue and it responds and adapts to the stress put upon it.</seg>
<seg id="9">When a two-year-old horse begins training the skeleton adapts, with bones getting stronger in response to training so that the horse can withstand the tremendous forces associated with galloping.</seg>
<seg id="10">Frequently this bone adaptation is associated with "shin soreness."</seg>
<seg id="11">Shin soreness is simply the cannon bone adapting to training.</seg>
<seg id="12">This occurs in every horse and, from time-to-time, it causes lameness.</seg>
<seg id="13">A horse still experiences further growth and maturity of the bones up to and past the age of seven.</seg>
<seg id="14">Therefore the bones of these young horses are not fully developed and this is seen clinically by the incidence of fetlock and knee chips, almost exclusively in young horses.</seg>
<seg id="15">Often at this time of the year, if there has been little rain, hard tracks can contribute to the incidence and frequency of bone soreness and bone problems.</seg>
<seg id="16">The concussive forces associated with galloping are passed up the leg and are absorbed by the bones, tendons and joints of the lower limb.</seg>
<seg id="17">If the young horse is not able to cope with these forces then soreness, lameness and bone chips are the likely result.</seg>
<seg id="18">Thus the training and racing required to gain entry into the Victoria Derby has acted as a natural selection process akin to Darwinian Theory - only the strong survive.</seg>
<seg id="19">This is not to say that concussion-related problems are only the domain of young horses.</seg>
<seg id="20">Already this spring, hard tracks, joint and foot problems have been associated with Puissance De Lune and It's A Dundeel.</seg>
<seg id="21">Even on Moonee Valley's renowned soft track, both horses were disappointing in last Saturday's Cox Plate with questions arising about Puissance De Lune's racing future.</seg>
<seg id="22">A horse racing over 2500 metres is probably similar to a human racing over 1500 metres.</seg>
<seg id="23">This means that these horse athletes need to perform both anaerobically and aerobically.</seg>
<seg id="24">The anaerobic component is short and allows the horse to sprint from the barriers to get a good position in the field.</seg>
<seg id="25">Aerobic performance relates to an athlete's ability to absorb oxygen during the event and convert that oxygen into muscle energy.</seg>
<seg id="26">When aerobic performance fails, this leads to the build-up of lactate in the muscles, which leads to fatigue and diminished performance.</seg>
<seg id="27">Thus the athlete with the better aerobic function can perform faster for longer.</seg>
<seg id="28">Many factors influence aerobic function or capacity - such as training, fitness, blood counts, muscle function - but two factors are critical, upper airway function and cardiopulmonary function.</seg>
<seg id="29">Horses can only breathe through their nose with this air passing through a narrow throat - larynx and pharynx and then down to the lungs.</seg>
<seg id="30">This means that good function in the throat is vital to an efficient airway and thus to aerobic function.</seg>
<seg id="31">Indeed, the throat is an area where horses have a lot of problems, such as roarers (a paralysed larynx), soft-palate displacement and pharyngitis.</seg>
<seg id="32">Without discussing the technical aspects of these problems, they all limit or reduce the amount of air getting to the lungs and clearly have a huge impact on aerobic function.</seg>
<seg id="33">Once the air reaches the lungs it needs to be delivered around the body to the muscles very efficiently.</seg>
<seg id="34">In this area a horse needs a good blood count and needs the heart to be an efficient pump.</seg>
<seg id="35">Any problem, albeit a minor one to any of these systems, will ensure that the horse will not run the 2500 metres.</seg>
<seg id="36">Oxygen is carried in the red blood cells, and we have seen that this can be improved by a number of factors.</seg>
<seg id="37">The illegal use of EPO as a doping agent is specifically aimed at increasing the red cell count.</seg>
<seg id="38">Similarly, altitude training causes the body to naturally produce more red blood cells to help the body cope and adapt to the lower oxygen in air altitude.</seg>
<seg id="39">It was stated in the media this week that last week's Cox Plate winner Shamus Award had been in a specifically designed and very expensive stable to mimic this high altitude.</seg>
<seg id="40">It will be interesting to see how the authorities act to such developments as our industry has always loved the charisma of the battler competing and beating the "big boys."</seg>
<seg id="41">In Saturday's Derby, the $4000 purchase Polanski, trained by Robbie Laing, will be the sentimental favourite for that reason.</seg>
<seg id="42">Finally, the horse's own endeavour and its ability to cope with pain is a factor.</seg>
<seg id="43">The great and successful racehorses all have this feature - they want to win and they seem to be able to compete with injuries and ailments that would normally make a horse uncompetitive.</seg>
<seg id="44">Pain will be a factor on Saturday, simply because we have young horses racing over a long distance.</seg>
<seg id="45">Perhaps all these factors mean that the winner of this classic race should be assured of a stud career because winning reflects superiority in so many areas.</seg>
<seg id="46">However, this is not always the case, which might explain the dominance of foreign horses in our best endurance race, the Melbourne Cup.</seg>
<seg id="47">Australian racing has a thirst for the quick riches and results that two-year-old racing offers, meaning that stallions and bloodlines producing precocious horses do well.</seg>
<seg id="48">Indeed, the Chris Waller-trained Zoustar, racing in Saturday's Coolmore Stud Stakes over 1200 metres, is hailed as the next superstar with a future stud career and a $20 million price tag.</seg>
<seg id="49">Dr Glenn Robertson-Smith is the founding partner of the Melbourne Equine Veterinary.</seg>
<seg id="50">Glenn is a specialist in equine surgery and consults both here and overseas.</seg>
</doc>
