<seg id="1">"Dark Universe," at the Hayden Planetarium</seg>
<seg id="2">American Museum of Natural History</seg>
<seg id="3">Dark Universe This Hayden Planetarium exhibition follows light to show the expansion of the cosmos.</seg>
<seg id="4">Mordecai-Mark Mac Low, a curator at the American Museum of Natural History, was showing off an exhibit about the history of the universe outside the Hayden Planetarium there eight years ago, he says, when a schoolteacher approached him and said, "You don't really believe all this Big Bang stuff, do you?"</seg>
<seg id="5">Shades of those bumper stickers and billboards you see in some parts of the country: "Big Bang?"</seg>
<seg id="6">You've got to be kidding - God.</seg>
<seg id="7">There is a mountain of evidence, still piling up, that the universe was "born in fire" 13.8 billion years ago.</seg>
<seg id="8">Cosmic space has been stretching ever since, taking the galaxies for a ride.</seg>
<seg id="9">Where, we don't know.</seg>
<seg id="10">And so, Dr. Mac Low said in an interview, the teacher's question planted a seed in his mind for "Dark Universe," the space show opening at the planetarium, in the museum's Rose Center for Earth and Space, this weekend.</seg>
<seg id="11">With a script by the esteemed science writer Timothy Ferris, directed by the museum's Carter Emmart and narrated by the planetarium's director and man about the cosmos, Neil deGrasse Tyson, the show promises to guide us through a century of discovery about the past, present and future of the universe.</seg>
<seg id="12">My reaction, both times I saw it, was that the century of discovery went by way too fast.</seg>
<seg id="13">Aficionados of the Hayden's space shows - this is the fifth - know that Mr. Emmart, the museum's director of astrovisualization, drawing on the enormous databanks of the world's astronomers, can take you on a trip that makes Hollywood's most vaunted special effects, including those in the hit "Gravity," look like a cartoon.</seg>
<seg id="14">So I was happily swooning through the cosmos, stars and galaxies floating crisply by like the fluff you get from blowing on a dandelion, ready to go anywhere, when the final credits started rolling.</seg>
<seg id="15">This is as good a place as any to applaud the selection of Dr. Tyson as narrator in place of the usual celebrities who have signed on in the past.</seg>
<seg id="16">Not that they were bad, but Dr. Tyson, a forceful presence and advocate of science whose many appearances on Bill Maher's cable show have gained him the nickname there of the Preacher, is a celebrity in his own right, soon to be the star of the revamped "Cosmos" TV series.</seg>
<seg id="17">He moves about the universe as comfortably and confidently as a man in his own kitchen.</seg>
<seg id="18">He knows what's in the refrigerator, what's good and what's stale, and how to rustle up a treat without a recipe.</seg>
<seg id="19">In the 25 minutes of the planetarium show, we hang out at the Mount Wilson Observatory, overlooking Los Angeles, where the expansion of the universe was first discerned, and cruise past the space station, which is carrying an instrument that physicists hope will identify the mystery sauce of the universe: dark matter.</seg>
<seg id="20">We dip into the clouds of Jupiter with the Galileo probe to retrieve evidence - a heavy form of hydrogen - that the whole universe was once hotter than the center of the sun, hot enough for forging simple atoms in the Big Bang.</seg>
<seg id="21">But atoms are only the beginning.</seg>
<seg id="22">The "Dark Universe" title is more than just poetic allusion.</seg>
<seg id="23">Discoveries in the last couple of decades, while underscoring the Big Bang, have revealed that the universe as now understood is a more complicated place than we can perhaps ever see.</seg>
<seg id="24">Only 5 percent of it consists of ordinary matter, made of atoms that we know and love.</seg>
<seg id="25">A quarter of the universe, by mass, astronomers say, is made of some invisible and not yet understood dark matter, which is detectable only by its gravitational pull on visible matter.</seg>
<seg id="26">And a whopping 70 percent of the universe is made up of an even more mysterious entity known as dark energy, a cosmic antigravity.</seg>
<seg id="27">We can't see that, either.</seg>
<seg id="28">As Dr. Tyson puts it at one point, "There's more to the universe than meets the eye."</seg>
<seg id="29">You might well wonder just how big a triumph a theory is that leaves 95 percent of the universe to the imagination.</seg>
<seg id="30">You might think that it's pretty cool that we still have so much of creation to discover.</seg>
<seg id="31">Or, if you tend toward cynicism, you might hark back to that bumper sticker: You must be kidding.</seg>
<seg id="32">You might also wonder how they are going to make a show out of dark stuff that you can't see and that few of us understand.</seg>
<seg id="33">The producers have gone easy on abstract explanations in favor of visual experiences, filling the dome with not just images of stars but also film shot at ground-based observatories and in space.</seg>
<seg id="34">There's something for everybody: Even kids who don't understand astrophysics will thrill to the hulking views of spacecraft like Galileo, Planck and the international space station passing overhead like the empire's battle cruisers in "Star Wars."</seg>
<seg id="35">But, as Dr. Mac Low and his colleagues show us, it is by following the light that astronomers have been drawn inexorably into the dark.</seg>
<seg id="36">If that sounds, well, Voldemortean, it is.</seg>
<seg id="37">One sequence, shown entirely in black and gray, shows tendrils of dark matter snaking across the sky, connecting and growing into a web, while sound effects that seem right out of a Harry Potter movie play in the background.</seg>
<seg id="38">These dark tendrils will form the cradles where stars and life will eventually form.</seg>
<seg id="39">As an example of the evidence for dark matter, we are shown a time-lapse view of a giant cluster of galaxies: trillions of stars and thousands of galaxies swarming together like bugs in a dish.</seg>
<seg id="40">Such compendiums of matter turn out to warp space like a lens, magnifying and distorting the images of galaxies even more distant.</seg>
<seg id="41">In the movie, those distorted galaxies swirl around the edges of the cluster like fish, so that the whole thing looks like an evil eye in space.</seg>
<seg id="42">"Dark Universe" opens on Saturday at the Rose Center for Earth and Space, Central Park West at 81st Street; 212-769-5100, amnh.org.</seg>
</doc>
