<seg id="1">Five ways to make the most of Aberdeen's International Street Market</seg>
<seg id="2">With everything from potted plants to pain au chocolat on offer, the International Street Market has something to suit all tastes.</seg>
<seg id="3">But instead of wandering the stretch of stalls without much thought, why not take a look at our guide to making the most of the three-day market.</seg>
<seg id="4">Who knows, you might pick up a bargain or two...</seg>
<seg id="5">Seek out the freebies</seg>
<seg id="6">Let's be honest, who doesn't love picking up a few free samples at markets?</seg>
<seg id="7">The stalls selling cheeses, breads and pastries will undoubtedly have some on display but you will hit the jackpot if the hot food stalls start up selling with trays of samples.</seg>
<seg id="8">Sniff out the freebies near closing time - you might just grab a plate of food for next to nothing.</seg>
<seg id="9">Eat seasonably</seg>
<seg id="10">Now that the weather has taken us into autumn, our shopping baskets should have changed with the seasons.</seg>
<seg id="11">But are you still picking up fruits and vegetables that are flown halfway across the world to your local supermarket?</seg>
<seg id="12">Then why not ask greengrocer stall holders for some advice.</seg>
<seg id="13">They can pick out the best produce and advise what to eat and what to avoid.</seg>
<seg id="14">Stallholders with a genuine passion for their products will have the best advice and may give you a couple of cooking tips to boot, giving you more for your money.</seg>
<seg id="15">Warm up with some exciting new cuisines</seg>
<seg id="16">Aberdeen may be teeming with restaurants offering cuisines from across the globe but the authenticity of some chain restaurants can be dubious.</seg>
<seg id="17">Look out for stallholders conversing in their mother tongue - if it matches their produce then it will have that authentic flavour.</seg>
<seg id="18">The colder weather is also perfect for French and Spanish street food, so indulge in crispy churros with oozing melted chocolate or a French crepe doused in icing sugar.</seg>
<seg id="19">Pick up some alternative dinner options</seg>
<seg id="20">The Saturday night dinner bell may herald the arrival of the takeaway menu but why not pick up something different to try?</seg>
<seg id="21">Butchers specialising in alternative meats are commonplace at international markets, so why not pick up some Springbok or Wild Boar burgers to widen your culinary horizons?</seg>
<seg id="22">For the same price as pre-made supermarket desserts you can also pick up a beautiful piece of patisserie at the French bakery stalls.</seg>
<seg id="23">If you don't want to go all out you can still pick up a couple of pieces of baklava to accompany your Saturday night curry - many stalls will work by weight so you can take only what you need.</seg>
<seg id="24">Try your hand at haggling</seg>
<seg id="25">It may be seen as a big no-no in the UK, but in these tough economic times there is no shame in negotiating a better price.</seg>
<seg id="26">Markets like these are a great starting point and you could walk away with a couple of pounds knocked off.</seg>
<seg id="27">If you plan on picking up a couple of items a good place to start is to ask the seller to throw in something extra.</seg>
<seg id="28">Plus its brilliant practice for negotiating better deals on big purchases like car insurance or electrical goods elsewhere.</seg>
<seg id="29">There are a wealth of tips online if you fancy a go and remember - the worst they can say is 'no'.</seg>
<seg id="30">Are you heading to the international market this weekend?</seg>
</doc>
