<doc docid="d9901cf9d0e9d0106b54b24b061782dc" genre="news" origlang="xx">
<seg id="1">New species of marsupial antechinus discovered by scientists</seg>
<seg id="2">The Kroombit Antechinus discovered bear Gladstone.</seg>
<seg id="3">Pic: Gary Cranitch Source: Supplied</seg>
<seg id="4">SCIENTISTS have discovered three new species of marsupial antechinus, one of which is living right on Brisbane's doorstep.</seg>
<seg id="5">One has been found at Samford, just northwest of Brisbane, one on the Tweed Volcano in the Scenic Rim to the city's southwest and a third at Kroombit Tops southwest of Gladstone.</seg>
<seg id="6">They were uncovered during research for the first field guide of Australian mammals.</seg>
<seg id="7">Antechinus - an animal a little bit bigger than a mouse - are renowned for their frenzied sex lives in which the male dies after mating with as many ladies as he can manage.</seg>
<seg id="8">It's not much better for the mums who have to carry up to 14 joeys in the pouch, just 2-3mm long.</seg>
<seg id="9">The discoveries bring the known number of antechinus to 13 and Queensland University of Technology mammalogist Andrew Baker will make that 15 soon, with two further finds in Tasmania.</seg>
<seg id="10">Buff-footed Antechinus found in Samford region.</seg>
<seg id="11">Pic: Gary Cranitch</seg>
<seg id="12">Antechinus are under pressure due to people clearing undergrowth and impacts from domestic cats and feral foxes.</seg>
<seg id="13">Some have even been killed by people thinking they are mice.</seg>
<seg id="14">Dr Baker said he expected some of the new species would be listed as endangered or threatened once the extent of their habitat and numbers was determined.</seg>
<seg id="15">He, with Queensland Museum senior curator Steve Van Dyck and Environment Department senior conservation officer Ian Gynther, have written the field guide over the past five years.</seg>
<seg id="16">Dr Baker said he expected more mammals were waiting to be discovered.</seg>
<seg id="17">``If you think about a place like Kroombit Tops that has been geographically isolated and you find a terrestrial thing like an antechinus, then why not other animals that have been trapped there as well?" he said.</seg>
<seg id="18">Tweed Volcano Antechinus from Springbrook NP and Border Ranges.</seg>
<seg id="19">``Animals there likely evolved in different directions and I think this is what happened with this antechinus.</seg>
<seg id="20">``It's a very exciting time to be a mammalogist.</seg>
<seg id="21">Dr Baker said two thirds of Australia's fauna was found in Queensland.</seg>
<seg id="22">``There are currently over 360 species of mammals in Australia and almost half of them are marsupials," Dr Baker said.</seg>
<seg id="23">``A further two dozen species have become extinct since European settlement but there are likely many other species waiting to be discovered - while the majority may be out in the bush, some could be within close reach.</seg>
<seg id="24">Last week James Cook University scientist Conrad Hoskin announced that he had found three vertebrate species new to science and isolated on Cape York for millions of years - a leaf-tail gecko, a skink and a frog.</seg>
<seg id="25">Dr Baker said he wanted families to turn off the television, take a torch and camera and head into local bushland to see what they could find.</seg>
<seg id="26">The field guide is on sale at the museum for $45.</seg>
</doc>
