<seg id="3">November 1, 2013 - 1:13PM</seg>
<seg id="4">Possible changes: Australian airlines are looking at the use of electronic devices on planes.</seg>
<seg id="5">Photo: Wayne Taylor</seg>
<seg id="6">The ability to read electronic books, watch videos on a tablet and even stream in-flight entertainment or use onboard wi-fi during the take-off or landing phase on planes is edging ever-closer - and passengers on US carriers are expected to be able to do so by the end of the year, writes The Australian Financial Review.</seg>
<seg id="7">The US Federal Aviation Administration has approved the use of electronic devices, excluding cellular communications, even when a plane is at an altitude of less than 10,000 feet, provided airlines conduct testing to prove such uses are safe.</seg>
<seg id="8">Mobile phones can be used when in flight mode.</seg>
<seg id="9">The timeline for a similar change to occur in Australia, where all airlines restrict the use of electronic devices during critical flight phases, remains less clear.</seg>
<seg id="10">A spokesman for the Civil Aviation Safety Authority on Friday said the agency was examining the FAA decision, but in the meantime the current restrictions remained in place.</seg>
<seg id="11">A Qantas spokesman on Friday said the airline was assessing the FAA ruling.</seg>
<seg id="12">"Our current policy is that electronic devices cannot be used during take-off and landing and we have no immediate plans to change that," he said.</seg>
