<seg id="1">Looting as Bolivia police go on strike</seg>
<seg id="2">LOOTING has broken out near Bolivia's presidential palace as junior members of the police force, angry over low wages, joined a nationwide mutiny.</seg>
<seg id="3">A crowd of some 200 officers, wearing civilian clothes and covering their faces, on Friday attacked the National Intelligence Directorate, smashing windows and pulling out furniture, documents, computers and even setting flags on fire.</seg>
<seg id="4">The Directorate, which also houses the police disciplinary board, is located one block from the main square in La Paz, where the presidential palace is located.</seg>
<seg id="5">"Mutiny, police mutiny!" chanted the protesters as they ransacked the office.</seg>
<seg id="6">Some 20 police stations in the country's ten main cities, including La Paz and Cochabamba, have joined the uprising.</seg>
<seg id="7">On Thursday, protesters took over the headquarters of the country's riot police, as well as eight other police stations.</seg>
<seg id="8">In an upscale La Paz neighbourhood, roughly 300 protesters hurled rocks and shattered windows at national police headquarters.</seg>
<seg id="9">Police on duty outside the building offered no resistance.</seg>
<seg id="10">The protesters, some of whom marched with their wives, also demanded the resignation of national police chief, Colonel Victor Maldonado.</seg>
<seg id="11">They are demanding to negotiate directly with President Evo Morales, who was in the presidential palace under heavy military protection.</seg>
<seg id="12">Interior Minister Carlos Romero, however, said in a statement that the government was willing to raise pay and engage in a "dialogue to find solutions."</seg>
<seg id="13">Police earn an average of $US195 ($194.58) a month, and want their lowest pay raised to $287 a month.</seg>
<seg id="14">Demands also include full pay upon retirement.</seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="ee314da46cc1b41071202c83019c2eb5" genre="news" origlang="xx">
<seg id="1">Yet another report on AFL knee injuries</seg>
<seg id="2">The AFL received an extremely good paper on knee injuries more than a decade ago.</seg>
<seg id="3">Picture: Wayne Ludbey.</seg>
<seg id="4">The "knee epidemic" has created an opportunity for an academic to make the chance to make a heap of money from the AFL today.</seg>
<seg id="5">When 14 AFL players - seven from the pre-season - have had surgery to reconstruct knees before April is off the desk calendar, a red flag will be raised at AFL House where the mantra is about protecting player safety.</seg>
<seg id="6">Mark Evans is the new AFL football chief with this brief.</seg>
<seg id="7">As with all his predecessors, the instant reaction is to commission a study paper.</seg>
<seg id="8">And there is nothing wrong with seeking more information.</seg>
<seg id="9">But the game has been here before.</seg>
<seg id="10">An extremely good paper was handed to the AFL more than a decade ago when serious knee injuries were unfolding at a more alarming rate than today when Adelaide is counting the loss of Taylor Walker, Fremantle with Kepler Bradley and Collingwood with Alan Toovey.</seg>
<seg id="11">It concluded:</seg>
<seg id="12">GRASS - in particular tightknit couch grass - contributes to knee injuries by catching feet.</seg>
<seg id="13">So the AFL ordered groundsmen to plant loose-strand rye grasses to offer more give to players as they dodged and weaved.</seg>
<seg id="14">HARD grounds are dangerous - as former Port Adelaide ruckman Matthew Primus can testify from the cricket square at the Gabba.</seg>
<seg id="15">So the AFL had the pitches removed from the MCG and demanded the same at the new Adelaide Oval.</seg>
<seg id="16">It also sought the hardness of AFL venues be regularly monitored and adjusted if there was a threat to player safety.</seg>
<seg id="17">KNOCKING of knees in ruck contests had contributed to a rise in posterior cruciate ligament damage.</seg>
<seg id="18">So the AFL changed ruck rules, demanding ruckmen stay in the centre circle for centre ruck duels rather than go on a Dennis Lillee-style run-up.</seg>
<seg id="19">But for all these changes, the knee curse is back.</seg>
<seg id="20">There will be new theories, such as the higher speed of the game and the bigger bodies increasing the threat.</seg>
<seg id="21">Even fatigue from a more demanding game will be put up as a cause.</seg>
<seg id="22">But none of speed or fatigue could be attributed to the Walker injury.</seg>
<seg id="23">It was in the first term.</seg>
<seg id="24">It was from an awkward landing on a ground that has been reconditioned to protect knees.</seg>
<seg id="25">And the Walker moment brought back a reminder of a very simple piece of reality the Crows accepted in 1997 after losing star forward Tony Modra to a knee injury in the 1997 preliminary final.</seg>
<seg id="26">The knee was not designed for Australian football, a game that works the body in every direction.</seg>
<seg id="27">There is no common link to the season-ending knee injuries to Walker, Toovey and Bradley at the weekend.</seg>
<seg id="28">Walker hyper-extended his knee on a landing.</seg>
<seg id="29">Toovey's gave way as he ran.</seg>
<seg id="30">Bradley had a Richmond opponent fall across his right knee.</seg>
<seg id="31">The AFL will meet the challenge of minimising knee injuries.</seg>
<seg id="32">Evans is certain to commission a new report.</seg>
<seg id="33">But as long as the game demands more of the knee than the joint was designed to do, knee surgeons will not go out of business.</seg>
</doc>
